A. Habitat. B. Habit. C. Flower.
</paragraph>
</caption>
<paragraph id="1E2DAB0A8D35C71FDCBCFACAF5FF0FF9" blockId="2.[136,1452,1281,1884]" pageId="2" pageNumber="32">
<emphasis id="2CE677188D35C71FDCBCFACAF41C0C66" bold="true" box="[189,325,1281,1307]" pageId="2" pageNumber="32">Discussion:</emphasis>
— 
<taxonomicName id="D992D0898D35C71FDD60FAC9F7620C66" authorityName="Hamzaoglu &amp; Koc" authorityYear="2022" box="[353,571,1281,1307]" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Brassicaceae" genus="Hesperis" kingdom="Plantae" order="Brassicales" pageId="2" pageNumber="32" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="muglensis">
<emphasis id="2CE677188D35C71FDD60FAC9F7620C66" box="[353,571,1281,1307]" italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="32">Hesperis muglensis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is similar to 
<taxonomicName id="D992D0898D35C71FDECAFAC9F61F0C66" authorityName="Huber-Morath" authorityYear="1965" box="[715,838,1281,1307]" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Brassicaceae" genus="Hesperis" kingdom="Plantae" order="Brassicales" pageId="2" pageNumber="32" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="pisidica">
<emphasis id="2CE677188D35C71FDECAFAC9F61F0C66" box="[715,838,1281,1307]" italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="32">H. pisidica</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
in habit and both also grow in the southwest of 
<collectingCountry id="6685EB9A8D35C71FD95AFACAF0F20C66" box="[1371,1451,1281,1307]" name="Turkey" pageId="2" pageNumber="32">Turkey</collectingCountry>
(
<bibRefCitation id="7A03D6FB8D35C71FDC91FAEEF4460C3D" author="Cullen, J." box="[144,287,1317,1344]" pageId="2" pageNumber="32" refId="ref4538" refString="Cullen, J. (1965) Hesperis L. In: Davis, P. H. (Ed.) Flora of Turkey and the East Aegean Islands. Vol. 1. Edinburgh, pp. 452 - 460." type="book" year="1965">Cullen 1965</bibRefCitation>
). However, it can be stated that serpentine rock is an important factor in the speciation of 
<taxonomicName id="D992D0898D35C71FD913FAEDF0FD0C42" authorityName="Hamzaoglu &amp; Koc" authorityYear="2022" box="[1298,1444,1317,1343]" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Brassicaceae" genus="Hesperis" kingdom="Plantae" order="Brassicales" pageId="2" pageNumber="32" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="muglensis">
<emphasis id="2CE677188D35C71FD913FAEDF0FD0C42" box="[1298,1444,1317,1343]" italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="32">H. muglensis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, because the area of distribution that partly overlaps 
<taxonomicName id="D992D0898D35C71FDEC4FA81F6660C1E" authorityName="Huber-Morath" authorityYear="1965" box="[709,831,1353,1379]" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Brassicaceae" genus="Hesperis" kingdom="Plantae" order="Brassicales" pageId="2" pageNumber="32" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="pisidica">
<emphasis id="2CE677188D35C71FDEC4FA81F6660C1E" box="[709,831,1353,1379]" italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="32">H. pisidica</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, in on calcareous bedrock. An evident difference in size between the basal and lower body leaves in 
<taxonomicName id="D992D0898D35C71FDE75FAA5F65E0CFA" authorityName="Hamzaoglu &amp; Koc" authorityYear="2022" box="[628,775,1389,1415]" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Brassicaceae" genus="Hesperis" kingdom="Plantae" order="Brassicales" pageId="2" pageNumber="32" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="muglensis">
<emphasis id="2CE677188D35C71FDE75FAA5F65E0CFA" box="[628,775,1389,1415]" italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="32">H. muglensis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
are striking. The basal and lower body leaves have a similar size in 
<taxonomicName id="D992D0898D35C71FDCDBFA59F4370CD6" authorityName="Hamzaoglu &amp; Koc" authorityYear="2022" box="[218,366,1425,1451]" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Brassicaceae" genus="Hesperis" kingdom="Plantae" order="Brassicales" pageId="2" pageNumber="32" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="muglensis">
<emphasis id="2CE677188D35C71FDCDBFA59F4370CD6" box="[218,366,1425,1451]" italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="32">H. muglensis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, but they are crowded around the base in 
<emphasis id="2CE677188D35C71FDF4FFA59F68B0CD6" box="[846,978,1425,1451]" italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="32">
<taxonomicName id="D992D0898D35C71FDF4FFA59F6970CD6" authorityName="Huber-Morath" authorityYear="1965" box="[846,974,1425,1451]" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Brassicaceae" genus="Hesperis" kingdom="Plantae" order="Brassicales" pageId="2" pageNumber="32" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="pisidica">H. pisidica</taxonomicName>
.
</emphasis>
The two species also differ in leaf shape. While the basal and lower stem leaves in 
<taxonomicName id="D992D0898D35C71FDE56FA7DF7B00CB2" authorityName="Hamzaoglu &amp; Koc" authorityYear="2022" box="[599,745,1461,1487]" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Brassicaceae" genus="Hesperis" kingdom="Plantae" order="Brassicales" pageId="2" pageNumber="32" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="muglensis">
<emphasis id="2CE677188D35C71FDE56FA7DF7B00CB2" box="[599,745,1461,1487]" italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="32">H. muglensis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
are oblanceolate-spathulate, they are oblong or oblanceolate in 
<taxonomicName id="D992D0898D35C71FDC89FA11F45D0C8E" authorityName="Huber-Morath" authorityYear="1965" box="[136,260,1497,1523]" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Brassicaceae" genus="Hesperis" kingdom="Plantae" order="Brassicales" pageId="2" pageNumber="32" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="pisidica">
<emphasis id="2CE677188D35C71FDC89FA11F45D0C8E" box="[136,260,1497,1523]" italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="32">H. pisidica</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
(
<figureCitation id="86A9B78F8D35C71FDD12FA12F42A0C89" box="[275,371,1497,1524]" captionStart="FIGURE 1" captionStartId="2.[136,229,1213,1235]" captionTargetBox="[561,1025,533,1188]" captionTargetId="figure-200@2.[561,1025,533,1188]" captionTargetPageId="2" captionText="FIGURE 1. Hesperis muglensis Hamzaoğlu &amp; Koç sp. nov. A. Habitat. B. Habit. C. Flower." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6520339" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6520339/files/figure.png" pageId="2" pageNumber="32">Figure 1</figureCitation>
, 
<tableCitation id="53109EB18D35C71FDD80FA12F48D0C89" box="[385,468,1497,1524]" captionStart="TABLE 1" captionStartId="3.[136,224,158,182]" captionTargetPageId="3" captionText="TABLE 1. Diagnostic characters of Hesperis muglensiss and H. pisidica." httpUri="http://table.plazi.org/id/4AEDFB828D34C71EDC89FF55F6CF09CA" pageId="2" pageNumber="32" tableUuid="4AEDFB828D34C71EDC89FF55F6CF09CA">Table 1</tableCitation>
). However, the differences that are the most striking between the generative characters are the width of petal limb, the length of the anthers and the ovary. The petal limb is narrower, the anther shorter and ovary glabrescent on valves in 
<taxonomicName id="D992D0898D35C71FDDF2F9E9F7D10F46" authorityName="Hamzaoglu &amp; Koc" authorityYear="2022" box="[499,648,1569,1595]" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Brassicaceae" genus="Hesperis" kingdom="Plantae" order="Brassicales" pageId="2" pageNumber="32" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="muglensis">
<emphasis id="2CE677188D35C71FDDF2F9E9F7D10F46" box="[499,648,1569,1595]" italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="32">H. muglensis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
. Furthermore, the ovary, especially on the margin parts has intensive secretion pubescence. Whereas, in 
<taxonomicName id="D992D0898D35C71FDE17F98DF7CA0F22" authorityName="Huber-Morath" authorityYear="1965" box="[534,659,1605,1631]" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Brassicaceae" genus="Hesperis" kingdom="Plantae" order="Brassicales" pageId="2" pageNumber="32" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="pisidica">
<emphasis id="2CE677188D35C71FDE17F98DF7CA0F22" box="[534,659,1605,1631]" italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="32">H. pisidica</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
the ovaries are without pubescence or have pilose pubescence (
<tableCitation id="53109EB18D35C71FD96DF98EF5CC0FF9" captionStart="TABLE 1" captionStartId="3.[136,224,158,182]" captionTargetPageId="3" captionText="TABLE 1. Diagnostic characters of Hesperis muglensiss and H. pisidica." httpUri="http://table.plazi.org/id/4AEDFB828D34C71EDC89FF55F6CF09CA" pageId="2" pageNumber="32" tableUuid="4AEDFB828D34C71EDC89FF55F6CF09CA">Table 1</tableCitation>
).
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="1E2DAB0A8D35C71FDCBCF946F46E0E21" blockId="2.[136,1452,1281,1884]" pageId="2" pageNumber="32">
<emphasis id="2CE677188D35C71FDCBCF946F7F70FD5" bold="true" box="[189,686,1677,1704]" pageId="2" pageNumber="32">
Specimens Examined:— 
<emphasis id="2CE677188D35C71FDDE3F946F7F70FD5" bold="true" box="[482,686,1677,1704]" italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="32">
<taxonomicName id="D992D0898D35C71FDDE3F946F7F30FD5" authorityName="Huber-Morath" authorityYear="1965" box="[482,682,1677,1704]" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Brassicaceae" genus="Hesperis" kingdom="Plantae" order="Brassicales" pageId="2" pageNumber="32" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="pisidica">Hesperis pisidica</taxonomicName>
.
</emphasis>
</emphasis>
